1
00:00:02,480 --> 00:00:06,030
People keep asking me questions
that I don't know the answer to.

2
00:00:06,240 --> 00:00:08,880
It's us that has the machine guns now.

3
00:00:09,600 --> 00:00:11,398
And it's them that's in the mud.

4
00:00:12,640 --> 00:00:14,119
Guns, Mr. Shelby.

5
00:00:14,200 --> 00:00:15,759
We'd pay good money.

6
00:00:15,840 --> 00:00:18,559
-For who do you speak?
-The Irish Republican Army.

7
00:00:20,960 --> 00:00:23,110
What are you? Copper?

8
00:00:23,200 --> 00:00:24,474
[GUNSHOT]

9
00:00:25,240 --> 00:00:27,709
You went after him because he was IRA.

10
00:00:27,800 --> 00:00:30,155
I followed him because I thought
he might have information.

11
00:00:31,640 --> 00:00:34,109
CAMPBELL: <i>The difficulty
with undercover work, Grace,</i>

12
00:00:34,200 --> 00:00:36,237
<i>is to remember what you are.</i>

13
00:00:36,760 --> 00:00:37,795
[GROANING]

14
00:00:38,040 --> 00:00:40,793
Your sister's in there giving birth,
there's one man should be here.

15
00:00:40,880 --> 00:00:41,880
TOMMY: You're right, Pol.

16
00:00:41,960 --> 00:00:43,917
On my oath. Tell Freddie it's safe.

17
00:00:46,160 --> 00:00:47,480
Welcome to the world, son.

18
00:00:48,560 --> 00:00:50,517
-Freddie!
-THORNE: Ada!

19
00:00:50,880 --> 00:00:52,234
Polly! Polly!

20
00:00:52,320 --> 00:00:53,920
The police came
and took his father away!

21
00:00:55,280 --> 00:00:56,634
[SPITS] You liar!

22
00:01:19,760 --> 00:01:25,836
<i>♪ Take a little walk to the edge of town
and go across the track</i>

23
00:01:27,480 --> 00:01:31,553
<i>♪ Where the viaduct looms
like a bird of doom</i>

24
00:01:31,640 --> 00:01:34,712
<i>♪ As it shifts and cracks</i>

25
00:01:35,800 --> 00:01:40,112
<i>♪ Where secrets lie in the border fires</i>

26
00:01:40,200 --> 00:01:42,111
<i>♪ In the humming wires</i>

27
00:01:42,200 --> 00:01:45,431
<i>♪ Hey man, you know
you're never coming back</i>

28
00:01:45,520 --> 00:01:47,511
<i>♪ Past the square, past the bridge</i>

29
00:01:47,600 --> 00:01:50,479
<i>♪ Past the mills, past the stacks</i>

30
00:01:52,360 --> 00:01:57,070
<i>♪ On a gathering storm comes
a tall handsome man</i>

31
00:01:57,160 --> 00:02:01,233
<i>♪ In a dusty black coat with
a red right hand ♪</i>

32
00:02:19,840 --> 00:02:20,840
[SIGHS]

33
00:02:26,600 --> 00:02:27,600
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

34
00:02:27,720 --> 00:02:28,720
Open up, love.

35
00:02:30,200 --> 00:02:31,880
I brought more things
for you and the baby.

36
00:02:31,960 --> 00:02:33,160
Got some fresh eggs and bread.

37
00:02:33,520 --> 00:02:34,749
-[BABY CRIES]
-Shh...

38
00:02:34,840 --> 00:02:36,160
POLLY: I'll leave it here.

39
00:02:36,320 --> 00:02:37,469
[BABY CRYING]

40
00:02:37,560 --> 00:02:39,836
Ada, think of the little one.

41
00:02:41,400 --> 00:02:43,471
Babies don't have principles.

42
00:03:06,120 --> 00:03:07,120
[DOOR OPENS]

43
00:03:12,400 --> 00:03:13,834
Did you speak to her?

44
00:03:15,040 --> 00:03:16,872
She didn't speak back.

45
00:03:19,840 --> 00:03:21,478
Did you tell her?

46
00:03:22,840 --> 00:03:25,275
I'll only tell her
what I know to be true.

47
00:03:27,880 --> 00:03:30,110
It's the last time
I'm going to say this.

48
00:03:30,280 --> 00:03:32,954
It wasn't me who shot Freddie Thorne.

49
00:03:35,640 --> 00:03:36,640
Tommy,

50
00:03:37,120 --> 00:03:39,430
I'd ask you to swear on the Bible

51
00:03:39,520 --> 00:03:41,193
but you can't swear on that, can you?

52
00:03:42,480 --> 00:03:43,834
Nothing you hold sacred.

53
00:03:49,560 --> 00:03:50,994
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

54
00:03:54,600 --> 00:03:55,600
There's tea.

55
00:04:01,720 --> 00:04:03,074
A new system.

56
00:04:04,080 --> 00:04:05,559
Everything in the diary, eh?

57
00:04:06,080 --> 00:04:07,080
Mmm-hmm.

58
00:04:12,280 --> 00:04:13,280
Black star.

59
00:04:13,520 --> 00:04:14,840
What does that mean?

60
00:04:15,320 --> 00:04:16,320
Black star day...

61
00:04:17,520 --> 00:04:20,194
is the day we take out Billy Kimber
and his men.

62
00:04:21,280 --> 00:04:22,759
No one knows this.

63
00:04:23,760 --> 00:04:25,512
Not even your family?

64
00:04:26,840 --> 00:04:28,194
Grace...

65
00:04:30,800 --> 00:04:32,677
Everyone in my family hates me.

66
00:04:33,680 --> 00:04:36,149
Why would I tell them?

67
00:04:36,240 --> 00:04:37,240
[DOOR CLOSES]

68
00:04:37,920 --> 00:04:39,336
He's off the bloody rails
is what he is.

69
00:04:39,360 --> 00:04:40,360
[MEN CHEERING]

70
00:04:40,440 --> 00:04:42,477
If he'll turn nose on his best mate.

71
00:04:42,560 --> 00:04:45,234
Bloody neighbors, John.
Snitch behind the curtain.

72
00:04:45,640 --> 00:04:49,315
Yeah, well, if you think that,
you're the only one who does.

73
00:04:49,560 --> 00:04:51,153
Look at this. Look.

74
00:04:51,240 --> 00:04:52,913
Bloody rakin' it in!

75
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:54,434
Who's running this carny?

76
00:04:54,520 --> 00:04:57,831
Name of Marsden. Intends on wintering
in Small Heath at this ring.

77
00:04:57,920 --> 00:04:59,513
-Does he?
-Only heard.

78
00:04:59,760 --> 00:05:04,596
Nobody in Small Heath craps in a pot
without the decree of Tommy Almighty.

79
00:05:05,040 --> 00:05:06,633
Mr. Marsden, I believe!

80
00:05:07,200 --> 00:05:08,270
The ring master!

81
00:05:08,720 --> 00:05:10,074
Proud I am to say so.

82
00:05:10,160 --> 00:05:12,151
Yeah, well, these here
are civilized parts.

83
00:05:12,960 --> 00:05:16,112
Man wants to set his stall up
with fellas lampin' each other.

84
00:05:16,200 --> 00:05:17,998
He needs himself a license.

85
00:05:18,240 --> 00:05:19,275
A license?

86
00:05:20,600 --> 00:05:21,600
For a fee.

87
00:05:22,600 --> 00:05:23,954
From those in charge.

88
00:05:24,040 --> 00:05:25,110
[CROWD CHEERING]

89
00:05:25,760 --> 00:05:26,795
I'll tell you what.

90
00:05:26,880 --> 00:05:30,555
How about I keep my money and you
shove a license up your ass crack?

91
00:05:30,720 --> 00:05:32,597
You don't want to speak to me like that.

92
00:05:32,680 --> 00:05:34,096
And who the bloody hell
do you think you are?

93
00:05:34,120 --> 00:05:35,155
[MAN SHOUTING] My name...

94
00:05:35,640 --> 00:05:37,233
is Arthur Shelby!

95
00:05:39,200 --> 00:05:40,200
Dad?

96
00:05:46,840 --> 00:05:47,840
Jesus.

97
00:05:53,240 --> 00:05:54,639
Thank you. You're a good boy.

98
00:05:57,200 --> 00:05:58,235
[SIGHS]

99
00:05:58,320 --> 00:06:00,789
Bless the father for these bounties
we're about to receive...

100
00:06:00,880 --> 00:06:02,359
Jesus Christ.

101
00:06:02,440 --> 00:06:03,589
Please, woman.

102
00:06:04,520 --> 00:06:05,669
Let me be.

103
00:06:06,560 --> 00:06:08,160
Finish your sandwich
and sling your hook.

104
00:06:10,120 --> 00:06:13,875
Polly Anna, I'm a guest
of the head of this family.

105
00:06:14,040 --> 00:06:17,158
So why don't you maybe tend to your
mangle or your scuttle?

106
00:06:17,240 --> 00:06:18,719
The head of the family ain't here.

107
00:06:23,520 --> 00:06:24,520
Tommy, uh,

108
00:06:24,760 --> 00:06:26,671
sometimes helps me with, uh,

109
00:06:27,200 --> 00:06:28,918
with business.

110
00:06:29,000 --> 00:06:30,000
[DOOR OPENS]

111
00:06:30,680 --> 00:06:33,433
-[DOOR CLOSES]
-Aye, well, speak of the devil.

112
00:06:35,520 --> 00:06:36,874
How are you, son?

113
00:06:38,760 --> 00:06:39,760
Get out.

114
00:06:40,840 --> 00:06:41,840
Come on, son.

115
00:06:42,880 --> 00:06:44,234
I'm a changed man.

116
00:06:45,360 --> 00:06:47,954
This family needed you 10 years ago.

117
00:06:48,640 --> 00:06:50,119
And you walked out on us.

118
00:06:50,720 --> 00:06:51,720
Not now.

119
00:06:52,040 --> 00:06:53,040
Get out of this house.

120
00:06:53,480 --> 00:06:55,312
-Tommy, he's different.
-Shut up.

121
00:06:58,760 --> 00:07:00,159
It's all right, son.

122
00:07:01,800 --> 00:07:03,074
Arthur Shelby...

123
00:07:04,120 --> 00:07:05,952
never stays where he's not welcome.

124
00:07:09,920 --> 00:07:10,920
[INHALES SHARPLY]

125
00:07:11,920 --> 00:07:13,638
Quite something you've become.

126
00:07:19,520 --> 00:07:20,520
Bye, son.

127
00:07:29,520 --> 00:07:30,520
[DOOR CLOSES]

128
00:07:32,080 --> 00:07:33,639
-He's our dad.
-[SCOFFS]

129
00:07:35,720 --> 00:07:37,631
He's a selfish bastard.

130
00:07:39,480 --> 00:07:41,517
You calling someone a selfish bastard?

131
00:07:43,680 --> 00:07:45,239
It's a bit rich, Tommy.

132
00:07:45,600 --> 00:07:46,600
I mean, thanks to you,

133
00:07:48,240 --> 00:07:50,709
we're already down a bloody sister.

134
00:07:51,480 --> 00:07:53,118
You want to see him, Arthur?

135
00:07:53,200 --> 00:07:54,599
You want to see him?

136
00:07:55,640 --> 00:07:56,640
You go with him.

137
00:08:12,880 --> 00:08:14,996
[DOOR OPENS AND CLOSES]

138
00:08:23,520 --> 00:08:24,520
[DOOR OPENS]

139
00:08:26,280 --> 00:08:27,280
Grace.

140
00:08:27,840 --> 00:08:30,673
I'm taking five pounds
from petty cash, all right?

141
00:08:30,760 --> 00:08:32,671
We don't have five pounds
in petty cash.

142
00:08:32,760 --> 00:08:34,512
Then I'll take what we've got.

143
00:08:34,840 --> 00:08:36,239
Count it and leave a receipt.

144
00:08:38,480 --> 00:08:41,552
Arthur, there are things in these books
I don't understand.

145
00:08:41,760 --> 00:08:42,795
Likewise.

146
00:08:42,880 --> 00:08:46,555
Every week we pay one pound,
ten shilling by postal order

147
00:08:47,360 --> 00:08:48,360
to a Daniel Owen

148
00:08:49,040 --> 00:08:50,758
-in London.
-Danny Whizz-Bang.

149
00:08:51,080 --> 00:08:53,754
Hangs around in the pubs
in Camden Town Wharf for us.

150
00:08:54,320 --> 00:08:57,073
Keeps his ears open for business.
He's a good man.

151
00:08:57,160 --> 00:08:58,600
I thought Danny Whizz-Bang was dead?

152
00:08:58,680 --> 00:09:00,512
Then you thought wrong, didn't you?

153
00:09:00,880 --> 00:09:02,757
But I've seen his grave. He was shot.

154
00:09:03,560 --> 00:09:05,915
That was a show to satisfy the wops.

155
00:09:06,480 --> 00:09:08,790
Tommy just shot
some sheep's brains at him.

156
00:09:10,240 --> 00:09:11,639
Who's buried in his grave?

157
00:09:16,440 --> 00:09:17,760
Now look, Grace.

158
00:09:18,600 --> 00:09:19,760
You know what's good for you.

159
00:09:19,880 --> 00:09:23,236
You don't ask questions about things
that don't concern you.

160
00:09:24,240 --> 00:09:25,674
Never, right?

161
00:09:26,720 --> 00:09:27,835
That's for you.

162
00:09:28,480 --> 00:09:30,676
Don't tell Tommy I took this.

163
00:10:00,320 --> 00:10:02,516
The boy needs a good hiding
if you ask me.

164
00:10:02,600 --> 00:10:04,830
Yeah, well, I'm this close
to giving him one.

165
00:10:05,640 --> 00:10:07,199
John and Ada too, sounds like.

166
00:10:07,280 --> 00:10:09,476
Nah, John moans on bloody principle.

167
00:10:10,000 --> 00:10:11,638
But if you saw his missus...

168
00:10:13,160 --> 00:10:14,195
Ah...

169
00:10:14,960 --> 00:10:16,758
You have a girl yourself, son?

170
00:10:20,040 --> 00:10:21,678
Perhaps when it suits, Tommy, eh?

171
00:10:24,080 --> 00:10:25,080
Yeah, well.

172
00:10:25,840 --> 00:10:27,319
He's been different.

173
00:10:27,880 --> 00:10:29,837
-You know, since the war.
-Yeah, well...

174
00:10:30,760 --> 00:10:32,478
A war can change a man.

175
00:10:33,240 --> 00:10:35,038
Speaking for myself, anyways.

176
00:10:35,120 --> 00:10:36,190
Where did you fight, Dad?

177
00:10:37,320 --> 00:10:39,072
Ah, all over, son.

178
00:10:39,520 --> 00:10:41,875
-All over.
-Yeah, all over.

179
00:10:41,960 --> 00:10:44,349
And the salvation of Jesus Christ

180
00:10:45,440 --> 00:10:47,431
spread his light over me.

181
00:10:48,120 --> 00:10:49,120
And as a pilgrim,

182
00:10:49,960 --> 00:10:51,837
I come to visit a new world.

183
00:10:52,440 --> 00:10:53,440
America.

184
00:10:54,040 --> 00:10:56,077
Where I beheld the future.

185
00:10:59,040 --> 00:11:00,040
Casinos.

186
00:11:00,160 --> 00:11:01,958
Money factories, son.

187
00:11:02,360 --> 00:11:05,478
Look, I've been studying
the competition.

188
00:11:07,080 --> 00:11:08,080
Their schemes,

189
00:11:08,720 --> 00:11:09,790
their systems.

190
00:11:10,040 --> 00:11:11,997
-Look at that. It's all there.
-Show me.

191
00:11:13,160 --> 00:11:15,470
There's a fortune to be made here.

192
00:11:17,120 --> 00:11:19,760
I'm an old man and my
heart's a battered vessel.

193
00:11:20,440 --> 00:11:21,440
But within,

194
00:11:23,400 --> 00:11:26,074
there still beats a fluttering
pulse of a dream.

195
00:11:28,360 --> 00:11:29,794
The Shelby...

196
00:11:29,880 --> 00:11:32,190
Casino and Hotel.

197
00:11:32,840 --> 00:11:36,117
Gents and dames will come flocking
from all corners.

198
00:11:37,080 --> 00:11:40,630
New York, Chicago, Boston,

199
00:11:40,880 --> 00:11:41,880
to the Shelby.

200
00:11:42,400 --> 00:11:46,314
Where I can stand proudly with
my dear children by my side.

201
00:11:47,360 --> 00:11:48,839
And the women there?

202
00:11:50,800 --> 00:11:52,518
Like fresh peaches.

203
00:11:53,080 --> 00:11:54,514
Thou could have a dozen.

204
00:11:57,680 --> 00:11:59,273
We'd all of us be kings.

205
00:12:00,120 --> 00:12:01,918
How much? How much to get started?

206
00:12:03,040 --> 00:12:05,190
The oak needs but an acorn.

207
00:12:07,480 --> 00:12:08,480
Let's do it.

208
00:12:09,800 --> 00:12:11,837
Let's do it. Let's bloody do it.

209
00:12:11,960 --> 00:12:15,669
It would make my heart beam, but
I don't want to cause any discord

210
00:12:15,760 --> 00:12:19,469
between the brothers. So please,
why don't you talk to Tommy first?

211
00:12:19,720 --> 00:12:21,870
No, now, I'm sick of taking
orders from him.

212
00:12:22,640 --> 00:12:25,678
Tommy's not the only one in the
family with a head for business.

213
00:12:27,800 --> 00:12:28,870
And Shelby money

214
00:12:30,160 --> 00:12:31,753
is Shelby money.

215
00:12:32,440 --> 00:12:35,910
I thank God for my wonderful sons.

216
00:12:37,880 --> 00:12:39,837
This is cause for a celebration.

217
00:12:39,920 --> 00:12:41,752
-Yeah.
<i>-Sláinte.</i>

218
00:12:41,840 --> 00:12:43,194
<i>Sláinte.</i>

219
00:12:49,360 --> 00:12:51,237
On your feet, soldier.

220
00:12:52,600 --> 00:12:54,591
On your feet.

221
00:12:57,040 --> 00:12:58,439
[RAUCOUS SHOUTING]

222
00:13:01,400 --> 00:13:02,736
Look, I don't wanna fight you, Dad.

223
00:13:02,760 --> 00:13:04,034
Come on, boy!

224
00:13:04,120 --> 00:13:05,872
I'm old enough to be your father.

225
00:13:13,760 --> 00:13:14,875
[GRUNTS]

226
00:13:15,600 --> 00:13:16,600
MAN: On your feet!

227
00:13:18,000 --> 00:13:19,115
Get up!

228
00:13:20,200 --> 00:13:21,200
All right!

229
00:13:23,720 --> 00:13:25,233
[CROWD CHEERING]

230
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:29,070
[GRUNTING]

231
00:13:32,840 --> 00:13:34,797
Is that all you got, boy?

232
00:13:41,400 --> 00:13:42,470
Get up!

233
00:13:53,840 --> 00:13:54,955
[SHOUTS] This here...

234
00:13:55,320 --> 00:13:57,357
is Arthur Shelby junior!

235
00:13:57,680 --> 00:13:58,750
My son!

236
00:13:59,280 --> 00:14:01,590
I love him and I'm proud of him!

237
00:14:01,840 --> 00:14:04,480
And he can fight any
one of youse in here!

238
00:14:05,120 --> 00:14:06,235
[CROWD CHEERS]

239
00:14:12,920 --> 00:14:13,990
You did good, son.

240
00:14:14,440 --> 00:14:15,440
You did good.

241
00:14:16,160 --> 00:14:17,160
I love you, Dad.

242
00:14:17,760 --> 00:14:20,036
I love you!

243
00:14:37,840 --> 00:14:38,840
Mr. Shelby?

244
00:14:40,640 --> 00:14:41,640
Who's asking?

245
00:14:42,760 --> 00:14:43,760
My name's Burn.

246
00:14:45,600 --> 00:14:48,240
I had word from your man in Camden town
you wanted a parley.

247
00:14:50,280 --> 00:14:51,634
Then parley it is.

248
00:14:54,080 --> 00:14:55,150
Few months ago,

249
00:14:55,280 --> 00:14:58,360
a man named Ryan came to this place with
a view to buying some goods from you.

250
00:14:59,720 --> 00:15:01,518
Mr. Ryan met with an accident,
he was shot.

251
00:15:02,400 --> 00:15:03,400
TOMMY: I heard.

252
00:15:03,680 --> 00:15:06,240
BURN: He was a man with a quick mouth.
I know that.

253
00:15:07,160 --> 00:15:09,151
Wondered if he made
any enemies in here?

254
00:15:09,240 --> 00:15:10,514
None that I know of.

255
00:15:11,080 --> 00:15:13,117
Not the kind of place to make enemies.

256
00:15:13,200 --> 00:15:15,714
-All are welcome here, Mr. Burn.
-Including Irish?

257
00:15:16,400 --> 00:15:18,198
Oh, especially Irish.

258
00:15:20,040 --> 00:15:22,998
Ryan told you he was a member
of the Irish Republican Army.

259
00:15:23,360 --> 00:15:25,192
Was he still welcome?

260
00:15:25,280 --> 00:15:27,954
Like I say. Any man who buys
beer is welcome.

261
00:15:28,040 --> 00:15:29,838
Perhaps you didn't believe him?

262
00:15:35,240 --> 00:15:38,073
In pubs, sometimes people say things.

263
00:15:38,160 --> 00:15:39,958
Sometimes it's the whisky talking.

264
00:15:40,160 --> 00:15:42,310
It's hard to tell which is which.

265
